{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Offline evals and canary tests are point-in-time measurements. A continuous eval pipeline runs on a sample of live production traffic every day, scoring a fraction of real requests and accumulating a quality time series. It catches gradual drift that no single eval run would detect \u2014 model updates, changing user patterns, and prompt degradation that builds slowly over weeks."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Continuous eval pipeline on production traffic",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Offline Evals Are Not Enough"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Offline evals run on a fixed test suite. Once that suite is stable, a high score tells you the model handles those cases well. It does not tell you:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Whether the distribution of real user requests has shifted since the suite was built"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Whether a silent model update from the provider changed outputs for edge cases not in the suite"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Whether a system prompt change three weeks ago introduced a subtle regression that has been accumulating"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Whether the quality floor is holding across a new user segment that started growing last month"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Continuous evals on production samples answer all of these. They are the production monitoring layer for LLM quality."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pipeline Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The pipeline has five stages that run on a schedule (typically every hour or every day, depending on traffic volume):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stage 1 \u2014 Sample Production Traffic"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Collect a random or stratified sample of requests that already flowed through your production system. You have the inputs and outputs; you need to score them."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import random, time, json\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass ProductionSampler:\n    \"\"\"Reservoir sampler for production LLM calls.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, capacity: int = 200):\n        self.capacity = capacity\n        self.reservoir: list[dict] = []\n        self.total_seen = 0\n\n    def observe(self, record: dict) -> None:\n        self.total_seen += 1\n        if len(self.reservoir) < self.capacity:\n            self.reservoir.append(record)\n        else:\n            j = random.randint(0, self.total_seen - 1)\n            if j < self.capacity:\n                self.reservoir[j] = record\n\n    def drain(self) -> list[dict]:\n        sample = list(self.reservoir)\n        self.reservoir = []\n        self.total_seen = 0\n        return sample\n\n# In your inference code, call sampler.observe() on every request:\n# sampler.observe({\n#     \"input\": user_message,\n#     \"system\": system_prompt,\n#     \"output\": model_output,\n#     \"timestamp\": time.time(),\n#     \"session_id\": session_id,\n# })"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stage 2 \u2014 Grade Asynchronously"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Never run the grader inline with the user-facing request \u2014 it adds latency and cost. Run scoring asynchronously in a background job that processes the sampled batch:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio\nfrom anthropic import AsyncAnthropic\n\nclient = AsyncAnthropic()\n\nJUDGE_SYSTEM = (\n    \"Score the response on a scale of 1 (poor) to 5 (excellent). \"\n    \"Output JSON only: {score: int, reason: str}\"\n)\n\nasync def grade_batch(records: list[dict], concurrency: int = 10) -> list[dict]:\n    semaphore = asyncio.Semaphore(concurrency)\n\n    async def grade_one(rec: dict) -> dict:\n        async with semaphore:\n            resp = await client.messages.create(\n                model=\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\n                max_tokens=128,\n                system=JUDGE_SYSTEM,\n                messages=[{\n                    \"role\": \"user\",\n                    \"content\": f\"Task: {rec['input']}\\nResponse: {rec['output']}\",\n                }],\n            )\n            import json as _json\n            try:\n                result = _json.loads(resp.content[0].text)\n            except Exception:\n                result = {\"score\": None, \"reason\": \"parse_error\"}\n            return {**rec, **result}\n\n    return await asyncio.gather(*[grade_one(r) for r in records])\n\n# graded = asyncio.run(grade_batch(sampler.drain()))"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Stage 3 \u2014 Store with Timestamp and Suite Hash"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import sqlite3, time, hashlib, json as _json\n\ndef init_db(path: str = \"continuous_eval.db\") -> sqlite3.Connection:\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n    conn.execute(\"\"\"\n        CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS scores (\n            id        INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,\n            timestamp REAL,\n            score     REAL,\n            session_id TEXT,\n            input_hash TEXT,\n            pipeline_version TEXT\n        )\n    \"\"\")\n    conn.execute(\"\"\"\n        CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_ts ON scores(timestamp)\n    \"\"\")\n    conn.commit()\n    return conn\n\ndef store_batch(conn: sqlite3.Connection, graded: list[dict], version: str) -> None:\n    rows = [\n        (\n            r.get(\"timestamp\", time.time()),\n            r.get(\"score\"),\n            r.get(\"session_id\", \"\"),\n            hashlib.md5(r.get(\"input\", \"\").encode()).hexdigest()[:8],\n            version,\n        )\n        for r in graded if r.get(\"score\") is not None\n    ]\n    conn.executemany(\n        \"INSERT INTO scores (timestamp, score, session_id, input_hash, pipeline_version) VALUES (?,?,?,?,?)\",\n        rows,\n    )\n    conn.commit()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Drift Detection Algorithms"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Once scores are in the time-series store, a drift detector runs after each batch to decide whether the current quality level has shifted meaningfully from the established baseline."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rolling Window Average"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest detector: compare the mean of the last N scores to the baseline mean."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def rolling_window_alert(\n    conn: sqlite3.Connection,\n    window: int = 100,\n    baseline: float = 4.0,\n    threshold: float = 0.3,\n) -> dict:\n    rows = conn.execute(\n        \"SELECT score FROM scores ORDER BY timestamp DESC LIMIT ?\", (window,)\n    ).fetchall()\n    if len(rows) < window // 2:\n        return {\"status\": \"insufficient_data\", \"n\": len(rows)}\n    scores = [r[0] for r in rows]\n    current_mean = sum(scores) / len(scores)\n    delta = current_mean - baseline\n    alert = delta < -threshold\n    return {\n        \"status\": \"alert\" if alert else \"ok\",\n        \"current_mean\": round(current_mean, 3),\n        \"baseline\": baseline,\n        \"delta\": round(delta, 3),\n        \"n\": len(scores),\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "EWMA \u2014 Gradual Drift Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Exponentially weighted moving average gives higher weight to recent observations. Better than a rolling window for detecting slow, sustained drift:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class EWMAMonitor:\n    def __init__(self, alpha: float = 0.1, baseline: float = 4.0, floor: float = 3.5):\n        self.alpha = alpha\n        self.ewma = baseline\n        self.baseline = baseline\n        self.floor = floor\n\n    def update(self, score: float) -> dict:\n        self.ewma = self.alpha * score + (1 - self.alpha) * self.ewma\n        alert = self.ewma < self.floor\n        return {\n            \"ewma\": round(self.ewma, 3),\n            \"floor\": self.floor,\n            \"alert\": alert,\n        }\n\n    def reset_baseline(self, new_baseline: float) -> None:\n        self.baseline = new_baseline\n        self.ewma = new_baseline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CUSUM \u2014 Abrupt Regression Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CUSUM (Cumulative Sum) detects when quality has shifted downward from the target and stayed there. It raises an alert faster than EWMA for sudden drops:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class CUSUMDetector:\n    \"\"\"Lower-sided CUSUM: detects drops below target.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, target: float = 4.0, k: float = 0.25, h: float = 4.0):\n        self.target = target\n        self.k = k    # slack = half expected shift\n        self.h = h    # decision interval (threshold)\n        self.S = 0.0  # cumulative sum\n\n    def update(self, score: float) -> dict:\n        self.S = max(0.0, self.S + (self.target - score - self.k))\n        alert = self.S > self.h\n        return {\n            \"S\": round(self.S, 3),\n            \"h\": self.h,\n            \"alert\": alert,\n            \"score\": score,\n        }\n\n    def reset(self) -> None:\n        self.S = 0.0"
          }
        ]
      },
